00:04:08.750 --> 00:04:09.835
There's other ones that--

00:04:09.835 --> 00:04:11.210
applications that
you're probably

00:04:11.210 --> 00:04:13.220
carrying around in your pocket.

00:04:13.220 --> 00:04:14.630
You can use the
fact that charged

00:04:14.630 --> 00:04:17.570
particles have very
finite ranges in matter

00:04:17.570 --> 00:04:20.760
to separate little bits of
that matter from other things.

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:23.090
So this is actually how
single-crystal sapphires

00:04:23.090 --> 00:04:26.900
can be separated in little
slivers for protective phone

00:04:26.900 --> 00:04:29.180
covers, because sapphire
is one of the most--

00:04:29.180 --> 00:04:31.430
the hardest, or the most
scratch-resistant materials

00:04:31.430 --> 00:04:33.500
there is.

00:04:33.500 --> 00:04:36.350
Single-crystal sapphire
is exceptionally strong,

00:04:36.350 --> 00:04:39.660
and optically transparent,
and expensive.

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:41.780
I know that because on
one of our experiments,

00:04:41.780 --> 00:04:46.190
we use a single-crystal sapphire
window to see into reactor

00:04:46.190 --> 00:04:49.790
conditions at like 150
atmospheres, and 350

00:04:49.790 --> 00:04:52.550
degrees Celsius, and
pretty corrosive chemistry.

00:04:52.550 --> 00:04:54.560
So you want to use as
little as possible.

00:04:54.560 --> 00:04:56.840
So you can use a big,
expensive accelerator

00:04:56.840 --> 00:04:58.850
to limit the amount of
sapphire that you use.

00:04:58.850 --> 00:05:01.070
And this is actually
done here in Boston.

00:05:01.070 --> 00:05:05.060
There's a facility not far from
here that uses an accelerator.

00:05:05.060 --> 00:05:08.120
And this is their
super detailed diagram

00:05:08.120 --> 00:05:10.440
of what the radiation
looks like--

00:05:10.440 --> 00:05:11.970
yeah, whatever.

00:05:11.970 --> 00:05:15.260
But what they do is they
take-- they accelerate protons.

00:05:15.260 --> 00:05:17.090
They send them through
bending magnets

00:05:17.090 --> 00:05:19.070
to steer that beam path.

00:05:19.070 --> 00:05:21.590
And then they send
them into a large piece

00:05:21.590 --> 00:05:23.690
of single-crystal sapphire,
which is exceptionally

00:05:23.690 --> 00:05:25.130
expensive to make.

00:05:25.130 --> 00:05:27.530
And they can actually
lift off a thin sliver

00:05:27.530 --> 00:05:29.480
with micron precision.

00:05:29.480 --> 00:05:31.100
The reason for that
is the same reason

00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:33.050
that we showed with
that SRIM code.

00:05:33.050 --> 00:05:36.140
If you have this exact
energy of protons

00:05:36.140 --> 00:05:38.120
going into well-known
matter, you

00:05:38.120 --> 00:05:40.930
know what its range is going
to be with an uncertainty

00:05:40.930 --> 00:05:42.740
or so of about a micron.

00:05:42.740 --> 00:05:46.070
So you can have things that
come out thin, uniformly

00:05:46.070 --> 00:05:49.180
thick, and smooth, right away.

00:05:49.180 --> 00:05:51.340
There's some other
really wacky products--

00:05:51.340 --> 00:05:56.020
like has anyone heard of
these betavoltaic batteries?

00:05:56.020 --> 00:05:56.990
No?

00:05:56.990 --> 00:06:01.040
They rely on beta decay or the
direct capture and electricity

00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:03.110
generation from a
radiation source

00:06:03.110 --> 00:06:04.730
like radioactive tritium.

00:06:04.730 --> 00:06:08.840
So in this little chip is about
2 curies worth of tritium.

00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:10.430
You guys will learn
in about a week,

00:06:10.430 --> 00:06:13.370
how to go from activity
in curies to mass,

00:06:13.370 --> 00:06:15.120
or something like that.

00:06:15.120 --> 00:06:16.550
And so this chip
actually contains

00:06:16.550 --> 00:06:18.620
a lot of radioactive
tritium that

00:06:18.620 --> 00:06:20.770
directly creates electricity.

00:06:20.770 --> 00:06:22.520
So you can hook into
that chip and produce

00:06:22.520 --> 00:06:24.800
nanowatts for years.

00:06:24.800 --> 00:06:27.170
So it's one of these
batteries that lasts-- well,

00:06:27.170 --> 00:06:31.280
as long as a couple half-lives
of the isotope that's inside.

00:06:31.280 --> 00:06:32.720
Now there's a trade-off here.

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:35.270
The shorter the
half-life, the more active

00:06:35.270 --> 00:06:38.000
a given isotope will be for
the same number of atoms,

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:39.830
but the shorter it will last.

00:06:39.830 --> 00:06:43.700
So you can have higher power
for lower time, or lower power,

00:06:43.700 --> 00:06:44.210
higher time.

00:06:44.210 --> 00:06:46.250
It's the classic
energy trade-off--

00:06:46.250 --> 00:06:50.440
works the same way
with irradiation.

00:06:50.440 --> 00:06:52.240
And so now I wanted
to get into some

00:06:52.240 --> 00:06:54.250
of the more technical
stuff, where

00:06:54.250 --> 00:06:56.920
we'll be talking about
nuclear mass and stability.

00:06:56.920 --> 00:07:01.240
And this is where the nuclear
stuff really begins in 22.01.

00:07:01.240 --> 00:07:04.100
First, I want to make sure
that we all agree on notation.

00:07:04.100 --> 00:07:07.410
So I'll be writing isotopes
in this sort of fashion,

00:07:07.410 --> 00:07:09.970
where we refer to A as
the atomic mass, or just

00:07:09.970 --> 00:07:12.040
the total number of nucleons.

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:14.680
This is not the exact
mass of a nucleus.

00:07:14.680 --> 00:07:17.830
It just refers to the sum
of the protons and neutrons

00:07:17.830 --> 00:07:19.123
in the nucleus itself.

00:07:19.123 --> 00:07:21.040
And a lot of what we'll
be talking about today

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:25.300
is the difference between
this nice integer mass number,

00:07:25.300 --> 00:07:27.100
and the actual mass
of the nucleus,

00:07:27.100 --> 00:07:29.950
and that difference is
given by the binding energy,

00:07:29.950 --> 00:07:33.170
or the excess mass, which
are directly related.

00:07:33.170 --> 00:07:35.420
Z is just referred to
as the atomic number,

00:07:35.420 --> 00:07:36.550
or the number of protons.

00:07:36.550 --> 00:07:38.450
It's what makes the
element what it,

00:07:38.450 --> 00:07:41.510
which makes the name
kind of redundant.

00:07:41.510 --> 00:07:43.760
But it's-- humans
learned by association.

00:07:43.760 --> 00:07:46.430
It's easier to remember
element names or symbols

00:07:46.430 --> 00:07:50.320
than which element is which
just by the number of protons.

00:07:50.320 --> 00:07:52.820
So a lot of times we'll use the
name, or at least the symbol

00:07:52.820 --> 00:07:54.280
just so we know what's going on.

00:07:54.280 --> 00:07:57.950
And anything up here is
some sort of a charge.

00:07:57.950 --> 00:08:01.520
I do want to warn you guys of
the dreaded multiple symbol

00:08:01.520 --> 00:08:03.860
use or multiple use of symbols.

00:08:03.860 --> 00:08:06.760
I'll try to stick
for a lower case q--

00:08:06.760 --> 00:08:08.270
will be charged.

00:08:08.270 --> 00:08:10.490
And uppercase Q
is going to refer

00:08:10.490 --> 00:08:13.190
to the Q value or the
energy consumed or released

00:08:13.190 --> 00:08:14.420
by a nuclear reaction.

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:16.310
So they're both Q's
but we're going to keep

00:08:16.310 --> 00:08:17.882
one upper and lower case.

00:08:17.882 --> 00:08:19.340
And like we mentioned
before, let's

00:08:19.340 --> 00:08:21.920
say we were to write a
typical nuclear reaction,

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:25.520
like the capture of
neutrons by boron

00:08:25.520 --> 00:08:29.180
to produce lithium-7,
helium-4, better

00:08:29.180 --> 00:08:33.200
known as an alpha particle,
and some amount of energy.

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:36.440
There's two places where we
actually use this reaction.

00:08:36.440 --> 00:08:38.960
One of them is as control rods.

00:08:38.960 --> 00:08:41.960
A lot of reactors use
boron for carbide,

00:08:41.960 --> 00:08:46.910
or this compound B4C, which
is conveniently solid, fairly

00:08:46.910 --> 00:08:50.450
dense, and contains a whole
lot of boron in one place.

00:08:50.450 --> 00:08:52.850
Specifically,
enriched in boron-10,

00:08:52.850 --> 00:08:55.910
because boron-10 has a high
cross section, or probability,

00:08:55.910 --> 00:08:57.308
for neutron capture.

00:08:57.308 --> 00:08:58.850
And the other one
is in what's called

00:08:58.850 --> 00:09:01.120
boron neutron capture therapy.

00:09:01.120 --> 00:09:04.003
Have I discussed this with
you guys already, BNCT?

00:09:04.003 --> 00:09:05.420
Good, because
that's what we'll be

00:09:05.420 --> 00:09:07.250
talking about for a few slides.

00:09:07.250 --> 00:09:09.980
And to write this whole
reaction is the same thing

00:09:09.980 --> 00:09:12.330
as writing this shorthand
nuclear reaction.

00:09:12.330 --> 00:09:14.412
So this is often how you
see them in the reading,

00:09:14.412 --> 00:09:16.370
and in papers, because
it's shorter to do that.

00:09:16.370 --> 00:09:19.187
But it's the exact same thing.

00:09:19.187 --> 00:09:21.270
So I have a couple of
questions for you guys then.

00:09:21.270 --> 00:09:23.870
I have this extra Q here.

00:09:23.870 --> 00:09:26.210
Where does that Q actually go?

00:09:26.210 --> 00:09:29.420
So let's say boron
and neutron absorb,

00:09:29.420 --> 00:09:32.660
it produces two nuclei with
different binding energies.

00:09:32.660 --> 00:09:34.670
What happens to
the excess energy

00:09:34.670 --> 00:09:38.260
created from the conversion
of mass to energy?

00:09:38.260 --> 00:09:38.840
Yeah, Alex?

00:09:38.840 --> 00:09:39.910
AUDIENCE: That could be heat.

00:09:39.910 --> 00:09:40.640
MICHAEL SHORT: Yep.

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:41.973
And heat, and more specifically?

00:09:41.973 --> 00:09:43.450
AUDIENCE: Kinetic energy.

00:09:43.450 --> 00:09:47.027
MICHAEL SHORT: Kinetic energy
of the radiation released.

00:09:47.027 --> 00:09:48.610
And so that kinetic
energy is actually

00:09:48.610 --> 00:09:53.350
used to our benefit in BNCT, or
Boron Neutron Capture Therapy.

00:09:53.350 --> 00:09:54.670
The way this works--

00:09:54.670 --> 00:09:56.440
once I hit play--

00:09:56.440 --> 00:10:00.100
is you can either-- you can use
any sort of source of neutrons,

00:10:00.100 --> 00:10:02.860
either a reactor
or an accelerator,

00:10:02.860 --> 00:10:05.267
through a lower complex
chain of events, like this.

00:10:05.267 --> 00:10:07.600
In this case, an accelerator--
so you don't need a whole

00:10:07.600 --> 00:10:08.680
reactor--

00:10:08.680 --> 00:10:11.590
fires a beam of
high-energy protons

00:10:11.590 --> 00:10:13.475
into a beryllium target.

00:10:13.475 --> 00:10:15.310
Does that sound fairly familiar?

00:10:15.310 --> 00:10:17.980
Firing something at
beryllium, releasing neutrons,

00:10:17.980 --> 00:10:19.690
like what Chadwick was doing?

00:10:19.690 --> 00:10:22.000
Except he was firing
alpha particles into it.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:23.890
This releases neutrons.

00:10:23.890 --> 00:10:27.040
What they don't have labeled
here is slowing down stuff,

00:10:27.040 --> 00:10:29.470
or probably
hydrogenous material,

00:10:29.470 --> 00:10:32.890
so that the neutrons slow
down to a lower energy.

00:10:32.890 --> 00:10:35.950
And their probability
of capture increases

00:10:35.950 --> 00:10:37.530
or their cross
section increases.

00:10:37.530 --> 00:10:39.447
And if you don't know
what a cross section is,

00:10:39.447 --> 00:10:41.760
the definition is
two slides away.

00:10:41.760 --> 00:10:45.280
And the idea here is that these
neutrons then enter the brain

00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:47.650
or wherever the
tumor happens to be.

00:10:47.650 --> 00:10:51.130
And we rely on the fact that
tumor cells consume resources

00:10:51.130 --> 00:10:54.370
much faster than regular cells,
especially neurons, which

00:10:54.370 --> 00:10:57.170
after you're about five,
don't tend to grow very much.

00:10:57.170 --> 00:11:00.340
So it's all downhill by the
time you enter kindergarten.

00:11:00.340 --> 00:11:04.390
And we use that to our advantage
so that the neutrons coming in

00:11:04.390 --> 00:11:06.850
will hit the cancer cells,
which will preferentially

00:11:06.850 --> 00:11:10.120
uptake the borated
compounds, leaving most

00:11:10.120 --> 00:11:11.470
of the normal cells intact.

00:11:11.470 --> 00:11:14.200
And the difference in
dose can be a factor of 5

00:11:14.200 --> 00:11:15.760
or a factor of 10.

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:18.370
So that the cancer gets fried
while doing as little damage

00:11:18.370 --> 00:11:21.250
as possible to the remaining
brain cells, of which we

00:11:21.250 --> 00:11:23.320
have fewer and fewer every day.

00:11:23.320 --> 00:11:24.910
So I say statistically
speaking you

00:11:24.910 --> 00:11:26.440
guys are probably
smarter than me

00:11:26.440 --> 00:11:28.670
if we go by number of
neurons in your brain,

00:11:28.670 --> 00:11:31.630
because I think I'm the
oldest person in the room.

00:11:31.630 --> 00:11:35.200
And so now we can start to
explain, how does BNCT work,

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:37.900
and why did we make the
choices that we did?

00:11:37.900 --> 00:11:41.350
For example, they use
30 MeV protons in order

00:11:41.350 --> 00:11:43.198
to induce these neutrons.

00:11:43.198 --> 00:11:45.740
So we have a nuclear reaction
that looks something like this.

00:11:45.740 --> 00:11:50.860
We start off with
beryllium-9 plus a proton--

00:11:50.860 --> 00:11:52.450
let's just call it
hydrogen to stick

00:11:52.450 --> 00:11:54.520
with our normal notation--

00:11:54.520 --> 00:11:58.540
and becomes-- well, can someone
help me balance this reaction?

00:11:58.540 --> 00:12:01.790
We know we get a neutron.

00:12:01.790 --> 00:12:02.975
What else is left?

00:12:02.975 --> 00:12:06.650
So Monica, what would you say?

00:12:06.650 --> 00:12:07.646
AUDIENCE: Let's see--

00:12:13.930 --> 00:12:16.430
MICHAEL SHORT: Even just say
number of protons and neutrons,

00:12:16.430 --> 00:12:18.040
and we'll figure out
the symbol later.

00:12:18.040 --> 00:12:20.648
AUDIENCE: Number of
protons should be--

00:12:20.648 --> 00:12:22.190
MICHAEL SHORT: Sorry,
oh, that's a 4.

00:12:22.190 --> 00:12:25.718
AUDIENCE: The number of
protons should be five.

00:12:25.718 --> 00:12:26.510
MICHAEL SHORT: Yep.

00:12:26.510 --> 00:12:30.420
Five protons, which
means it's boron.

00:12:30.420 --> 00:12:32.578
And number of neutrons
in the nucleus?

00:12:32.578 --> 00:12:33.120
Someone else?

00:12:35.917 --> 00:12:36.417
Yeah?

00:12:36.417 --> 00:12:37.437
AUDIENCE: Nine.

00:12:37.437 --> 00:12:38.270
MICHAEL SHORT: Nine.

00:12:38.270 --> 00:12:41.450
So we have boron-9.

00:12:41.450 --> 00:12:44.330
Not a stable isotope of boron,
but it doesn't really matter,

00:12:44.330 --> 00:12:47.960
because boron-9 almost
immediately decays into

00:12:47.960 --> 00:12:52.310
an alpha, and an
alpha, and a hydrogen.

00:12:52.310 --> 00:12:54.628
But this nuclear
reaction right here

00:12:54.628 --> 00:12:56.420
is what we'll be studying
for a little bit.

00:12:56.420 --> 00:13:00.830
And there'll also be
some amount of energy.

00:13:00.830 --> 00:13:04.490
And this Q can actually
be positive or negative.

00:13:04.490 --> 00:13:06.710
No one said there had
to be energy released

00:13:06.710 --> 00:13:09.450
in a nuclear reaction,
because in this case,

00:13:09.450 --> 00:13:18.540
we actually start off with 30
MeV protons and roughly zero

00:13:18.540 --> 00:13:19.998
MeV beryllium.

00:13:19.998 --> 00:13:21.540
If you want to get
really exact, it's

00:13:21.540 --> 00:13:25.050
on the order of
about 0.01 eV, which

00:13:25.050 --> 00:13:27.810
is why we neglect the
kinetic energy of beryllium

00:13:27.810 --> 00:13:29.870
at room temperature.

00:13:29.870 --> 00:13:31.960
There are other
reactions that when

00:13:31.960 --> 00:13:34.150
you fire a proton
into them will produce

00:13:34.150 --> 00:13:36.547
neutrons, such as the
absorption of lithium.

00:13:36.547 --> 00:13:38.380
But can anyone think
of why we'd want to use

00:13:38.380 --> 00:13:39.880
beryllium instead of lithium?

00:13:46.895 --> 00:13:48.020
Kristin, what do you think?

00:13:48.020 --> 00:13:50.340
What could be a bad thing
about using lithium?

00:13:53.140 --> 00:13:54.984
You ever throw in water?

00:13:54.984 --> 00:13:55.880
AUDIENCE: No.

00:13:55.880 --> 00:13:56.630
MICHAEL SHORT: OK.

00:13:56.630 --> 00:13:58.088
Then I should show
you what happens

00:13:58.088 --> 00:14:00.110
when you throw it in water.

00:14:00.110 --> 00:14:01.850
There's a few bad
things about lithium.

00:14:01.850 --> 00:14:04.400
It does this when you
throw it in water.

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:06.170
It's one of the alkali metals.

00:14:06.170 --> 00:14:08.540
It's got an awfully
low melting point.

00:14:08.540 --> 00:14:10.910
It reacts with oxygen to
produce an oxide almost

00:14:10.910 --> 00:14:11.880
instantaneously.

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:13.760
So if you ever take a
lithium battery apart,

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:16.700
which you shouldn't, but if
you watch the video of somebody

00:14:16.700 --> 00:14:19.340
else doing it, you'll see that
the lithium foil turns black

00:14:19.340 --> 00:14:20.570
almost instantly.

00:14:20.570 --> 00:14:22.550
It also has a pretty
poor thermal conductivity

00:14:22.550 --> 00:14:25.610
and doesn't hold that structural
integrity when it melts.

00:14:25.610 --> 00:14:28.518
So it's not that good
of a target to use.

00:14:28.518 --> 00:14:30.560
Beryllium's pretty cool
in that it's the lightest

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:32.275
structural material there is.

00:14:32.275 --> 00:14:33.650
Folks tend to make
satellites out

00:14:33.650 --> 00:14:35.690
of it, because it
costs a lot of money

00:14:35.690 --> 00:14:37.077
to launch things into space.

00:14:37.077 --> 00:14:39.410
And if you want something
that has a high melting point,

00:14:39.410 --> 00:14:42.440
and is light, and is structural,
beryllium's your way to go.

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:45.800
It also happens to be a
great neutron generator.

00:14:45.800 --> 00:14:48.230
And then why 30 MeV?

00:14:48.230 --> 00:14:51.950
In this case, we're going
to use a table called JANIS,

00:14:51.950 --> 00:14:56.230
