00:17:19.020 --> 00:17:21.240
Then another question
is, how does the boron

00:17:21.240 --> 00:17:23.220
only get into the cancer cells?

00:17:23.220 --> 00:17:24.810
Like we mentioned
before, cancer cells

00:17:24.810 --> 00:17:26.609
are actively
growing, which means

00:17:26.609 --> 00:17:29.820
they need a very large
and active blood supply.

00:17:29.820 --> 00:17:32.670
And so it's one way for
things to, let's say,

00:17:32.670 --> 00:17:34.980
not quite cross the
blood-brain barrier.

00:17:34.980 --> 00:17:38.190
If the cancer cells are growing
and your neurons aren't, then

00:17:38.190 --> 00:17:40.605
your cancer cells are going
to use more energy, take

00:17:40.605 --> 00:17:43.290
in more sugar, which
might be doped with boron,

00:17:43.290 --> 00:17:45.005
or some other compound
doped with boron,

00:17:45.005 --> 00:17:47.130
and that's all you can get
the boron into the cells

00:17:47.130 --> 00:17:48.960
that you want.

00:17:48.960 --> 00:17:51.870
And then why was boron
selected for the therapy?

00:17:51.870 --> 00:17:53.130
Let's think about that.

00:17:53.130 --> 00:17:58.490
What happens after the
neutron is created?

00:17:58.490 --> 00:18:02.180
And let's write the next
stage of the reaction.

00:18:02.180 --> 00:18:03.870
In boron neutron
capture therapy,

00:18:03.870 --> 00:18:10.260
we rely on doping the patient
with boron-10 to release

00:18:10.260 --> 00:18:21.510
an alpha particle, and
lithium-7 and a gamma ray.

00:18:21.510 --> 00:18:22.922
So now what we
can start doing is

00:18:22.922 --> 00:18:25.380
look at the table of nuclides,
which I'm going to teach you

00:18:25.380 --> 00:18:27.630
how to read now, to
figure out-- let's

00:18:27.630 --> 00:18:31.560
say that this neutron had
an energy of about zero eV

00:18:31.560 --> 00:18:36.120
and the boron nucleus had
an energy of about zero eV.

00:18:36.120 --> 00:18:42.780
And in the end, all this
stuff here has gained or lost

00:18:42.780 --> 00:18:45.360
some sort of energy
cue, Q. And today we're

00:18:45.360 --> 00:18:47.200
going to teach you how
to calculate this Q.

00:18:47.200 --> 00:18:51.330
So I want to skip ahead to how
to read the table of nuclides.

00:18:51.330 --> 00:18:53.320
So there's all-- this is
like the poster you'll

00:18:53.320 --> 00:18:54.570
see in every nuclear building.

00:18:54.570 --> 00:18:57.303
It's kind of what makes us, us.

00:18:57.303 --> 00:18:59.220
What you'll notice is
that there's a whole lot

00:18:59.220 --> 00:19:01.070
of nuclei at the lower left.

00:19:01.070 --> 00:19:02.940
They are the light ones.

00:19:02.940 --> 00:19:05.340
At the upper right, they
are the heavier ones.

00:19:05.340 --> 00:19:08.040
And they're colored
by half-life.

00:19:08.040 --> 00:19:10.620
In general, the blue
ones will be stable,

00:19:10.620 --> 00:19:13.320
and the further away you get
from blue, the less stable

00:19:13.320 --> 00:19:14.185
they get.

00:19:14.185 --> 00:19:16.560
So right away, without even
delving deeper, what patterns

00:19:16.560 --> 00:19:17.560
do you guys notice here?

00:19:20.140 --> 00:19:22.310
Yeah, Alex?

00:19:22.310 --> 00:19:24.897
AUDIENCE: As they get bigger,
heavier, they're more unstable.

00:19:24.897 --> 00:19:25.730
MICHAEL SHORT: Yeah.

00:19:25.730 --> 00:19:29.082
There's a whole section
where there's no more blue.

00:19:29.082 --> 00:19:30.290
There are no stable elements.

00:19:30.290 --> 00:19:33.590
So stability drops off
after a certain point.

00:19:33.590 --> 00:19:36.890
And what about in the
region of stable isotopes?

00:19:36.890 --> 00:19:38.950
Does anybody notice any
repeating patterns here?

00:19:42.960 --> 00:19:45.000
Take a look at every other row.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:47.040
There's a bunch of
blues and then one,

00:19:47.040 --> 00:19:51.090
and then a bunch and then one,
and then more and then none.

00:19:51.090 --> 00:19:53.310
That must be technetium,
because that's

00:19:53.310 --> 00:19:55.920
the only element around
there that doesn't have any.

00:19:55.920 --> 00:19:57.050
And then a bunch of blues.

00:19:57.050 --> 00:19:59.310
So every other row--

00:19:59.310 --> 00:20:02.550
and in this case, it's
increasing number of protons--

00:20:02.550 --> 00:20:05.490
has more or fewer
stable isotopes.

00:20:05.490 --> 00:20:08.280
It turns out that
the even numbered

00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:11.070
