It's the difference
between the actual mass

00:23:44.450 --> 00:23:47.870
and a fairly poor
approximation of the mass.

00:23:47.870 --> 00:23:50.060
So the excess mass
doesn't really

00:23:50.060 --> 00:23:53.160
have that much of a
physical connotation.

00:23:53.160 --> 00:23:56.180
But it is nice, because
if you know very well

00:23:56.180 --> 00:23:58.790
the tabulated atomic number--

00:23:58.790 --> 00:24:02.240
I'm sorry, the-- yeah, the mass
number and the excess mass,

00:24:02.240 --> 00:24:04.100
you can figure out--

00:24:04.100 --> 00:24:06.020
let's see-- yeah,
you can figure out

00:24:06.020 --> 00:24:07.640
what the real atomic mass is.

00:24:10.350 --> 00:24:14.130
And I want to switch now to
the actual table of nuclides

00:24:14.130 --> 00:24:16.420
and show you one example.

00:24:16.420 --> 00:24:18.510
If you want to very quickly
jump between isotopes,

00:24:18.510 --> 00:24:21.302
you can type them
in right up here.

00:24:21.302 --> 00:24:23.760
And does anyone know what the
gold standard for atomic mass

00:24:23.760 --> 00:24:24.260
is?

00:24:24.260 --> 00:24:26.010
And I'll give you a
hint, it's not gold.

00:24:26.010 --> 00:24:26.510
Yep?

00:24:26.510 --> 00:24:27.510
AUDIENCE: Carbon-12.

00:24:27.510 --> 00:24:28.860
MICHAEL SHORT: Carbon-12.

00:24:28.860 --> 00:24:31.653
What do you think the
excess mass of carbon-12

00:24:31.653 --> 00:24:33.570
is going to be without
doing any calculations?

00:24:33.570 --> 00:24:34.500
AUDIENCE: Zero.

00:24:34.500 --> 00:24:35.600
MICHAEL SHORT: Exactly.

00:24:35.600 --> 00:24:36.990
Zero.

00:24:36.990 --> 00:24:40.230
So if we go to
carbon-12, because that

00:24:40.230 --> 00:24:44.250
is set as the standard, the
way atomic masses were done

00:24:44.250 --> 00:24:48.540
was carbon-12 weighs
exactly 12 AMU.

00:24:48.540 --> 00:24:51.480
The excess mass here is zero.

00:24:51.480 --> 00:24:55.320
And that's why the atomic mass
is 12.0 to as many decimals

00:24:55.320 --> 00:24:58.060
as we care to note.

00:24:58.060 --> 00:25:00.230
So is everyone clear
on what excess mass is?

00:25:00.230 --> 00:25:00.730
Yep?

00:25:00.730 --> 00:25:04.360
AUDIENCE: What's the point of
c squared for that conversion?

00:25:04.360 --> 00:25:06.970
MICHAEL SHORT: So mass
does not actually equal--

00:25:06.970 --> 00:25:09.035
oh right, and it's
actually on the--

00:25:09.035 --> 00:25:10.700
where did my chalk go?

00:25:10.700 --> 00:25:14.830
It's actually down below.

00:25:14.830 --> 00:25:18.180
The point is that energy is
related to mass by c squared.

00:25:18.180 --> 00:25:19.930
So they're not the
same units, but they're

00:25:19.930 --> 00:25:21.536
directly convertible.

00:25:21.536 --> 00:25:22.410
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:25:22.410 --> 00:25:23.470
MICHAEL SHORT: Yep.

00:25:23.470 --> 00:25:26.410
And so this way, you have
an E over a c squared.

00:25:26.410 --> 00:25:28.610
You get an m, and there we go.

00:25:28.610 --> 00:25:31.620
I had the units upside down.

00:25:31.620 --> 00:25:38.570
However, carbon-12 does not
have a zero binding energy.

00:25:38.570 --> 00:25:39.370
Yeah, Luke?

00:25:39.370 --> 00:25:41.815
AUDIENCE: How come when
you did that calculation,

00:25:41.815 --> 00:25:44.140
you didn't use the c squared?

00:25:44.140 --> 00:25:49.750
So like, it seems like then
that would be 26.0159--

00:25:49.750 --> 00:25:51.840
MICHAEL SHORT:
MeV per c squared.

00:25:51.840 --> 00:25:52.340
Yeah.

00:25:52.340 --> 00:25:54.980
AUDIENCE: But they don't
say that up there--

00:25:54.980 --> 00:25:57.435
or it didn't say
that on the table.

00:25:57.435 --> 00:25:58.810
MICHAEL SHORT:
Yeah, that's true.

00:25:58.810 --> 00:26:02.650
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:02.650 --> 00:26:04.660
MICHAEL SHORT: So
it is funny, right?

00:26:04.660 --> 00:26:07.090
The binding energy is give it
in keV, and that's correct.

00:26:07.090 --> 00:26:08.500
An energy is an energy.

00:26:08.500 --> 00:26:10.730
An excess mass, it
really should say

00:26:10.730 --> 00:26:14.290
keV per c squared, because if
we're talking in units of mass,

00:26:14.290 --> 00:26:16.540
it's got to be in m.

00:26:16.540 --> 00:26:21.710
Or in this way, you could say
m is an energy per c squared.

00:26:21.710 --> 00:26:26.020
So this, to me, is a semantic
inconsistency in the table.

00:26:26.020 --> 00:26:28.120
But you guys will know
that a mass is always

00:26:28.120 --> 00:26:31.270
going to be an AMU,
or kilograms, or MeV

00:26:31.270 --> 00:26:32.730
per c squared.

00:26:32.730 --> 00:26:37.150
And energies will be in
MeV, keV, some sort of eV,

00:26:37.150 --> 00:26:39.370
usually, in this course.

00:26:39.370 --> 00:26:41.520
The binding energy,
though, that's correct.

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:44.280
That's in keV, because
that's an actual energy.

00:26:44.280 --> 00:26:46.530
Now then the question is,
what does the binding energy

00:26:46.530 --> 00:26:47.580
actually represent?

00:26:47.580 --> 00:26:49.680
Does anyone remember
from Friday or Thursday?

00:26:54.762 --> 00:26:56.470
I can refresh your
memory, because that's

00:26:56.470 --> 00:26:58.800
what I'm here to do.

00:26:58.800 --> 00:27:00.850
The binding energy
is as if-- let's say

00:27:00.850 --> 00:27:05.600
we're assembling carbon-12
from its constituent nucleons.

00:27:05.600 --> 00:27:06.970
There's going to be 12 of them.

00:27:09.750 --> 00:27:14.565
Let's say we had six
protons and six neutrons.

00:27:17.300 --> 00:27:21.080
We can calculate the
total mass energy

00:27:21.080 --> 00:27:24.560
of this ensemble of nucleons
when they're infinitely

00:27:24.560 --> 00:27:25.730
far apart from each other.

00:27:25.730 --> 00:27:27.110
And forgive the little--

00:27:27.110 --> 00:27:28.370
it's not to scale.

00:27:28.370 --> 00:27:31.820
But they are infinitely
far apart from each other.

00:27:31.820 --> 00:27:34.350
And we can say that--

00:27:34.350 --> 00:27:37.780
let's say there is
Z number of protons.

00:27:37.780 --> 00:27:40.080
So we'll say the
binding energy is

00:27:40.080 --> 00:27:44.910
the number of protons
times the mass of a proton

00:27:44.910 --> 00:27:48.150
plus the number of neutrons--

00:27:48.150 --> 00:27:51.600
A minus Z-- times
the mass of a neutron

00:27:51.600 --> 00:27:55.950
minus the energy of the
assembled carbon-12 nucleus.

00:28:03.700 --> 00:28:05.860
So there's actually a
measurable difference

00:28:05.860 --> 00:28:10.590
in mass between six
protons and six neutrons,

00:28:10.590 --> 00:28:16.980
and the actual mass of a nucleus
with atomic number A and--

00:28:16.980 --> 00:28:22.026
I'm sorry, with atomic number
Z and mass number A c squared.

00:28:25.760 --> 00:28:28.360
So is everyone clear on how
we arrived at this formula?

00:28:28.360 --> 00:28:30.310
It's effectively
the energy released

00:28:30.310 --> 00:28:34.180
when you take the individual
nucleons, assemble the nucleus.

00:28:34.180 --> 00:28:36.430
You don't have as much
mass as when you started.

00:28:36.430 --> 00:28:38.620
Or in some cases, you might
have a little more mass

00:28:38.620 --> 00:28:42.760
than when you started if things
are particularly unstable.

00:28:42.760 --> 00:28:45.730
And you can use the excess
mass and binding energies

00:28:45.730 --> 00:28:50.320
in relative amounts to see, is
a nucleus going to be stable?

00:28:50.320 --> 00:28:53.500
For example, let's
look at iron-55 I'm

00:28:53.500 --> 00:28:56.150
going to jump here,
make it a little bigger

00:28:56.150 --> 00:28:59.560
so the important stuff
is easier to see.

00:28:59.560 --> 00:29:03.657
And if you notice, the
binding energy of iron-55--

00:29:03.657 --> 00:29:04.740
there's quite a bit of it.

00:29:04.740 --> 00:29:05.940
It's very well-bound.

00:29:05.940 --> 00:29:09.780
In fact, this is one of
the most well-bound nuclei

00:29:09.780 --> 00:29:12.330
in the whole chart of nuclides.

00:29:12.330 --> 00:29:13.830
Let's look at
something that we know

00:29:13.830 --> 00:29:16.400
to be particularly unstable.

00:29:16.400 --> 00:29:18.670
Someone have any idea?

00:29:18.670 --> 00:29:21.580
Let's just add like
20 neutrons to iron

00:29:21.580 --> 00:29:23.810
let's see if it even exists.

00:29:23.810 --> 00:29:25.260
No-- doesn't happen.

00:29:25.260 --> 00:29:28.930
Let's try adding 10
neutrons to iron--

00:29:28.930 --> 00:29:30.100
or go even crazier.

00:29:32.720 --> 00:29:35.570
What about 70?

00:29:35.570 --> 00:29:39.090
Too small-- all right, let's
meet somewhere in the middle--

00:29:39.090 --> 00:29:40.780
68.

00:29:40.780 --> 00:29:42.238
Still a pretty high
binding energy,

00:29:42.238 --> 00:29:43.822
but you can look at
it as a difference

00:29:43.822 --> 00:29:45.175
in binding energy per nucleon.

00:29:48.190 --> 00:29:50.500
So in this case, the
binding energy per nucleon--

00:29:50.500 --> 00:29:52.660
if you take the binding
energy and divide

00:29:52.660 --> 00:29:54.580
by the total number of
nucleons, will give you

00:29:54.580 --> 00:29:58.660
a relative measure of how
tightly bound that nucleus is.

00:29:58.660 --> 00:30:00.430
Now these are not
absolute things.

00:30:00.430 --> 00:30:02.630
You can't just say,
certain binding energy

00:30:02.630 --> 00:30:04.630
leads to certain stability,
but they do give you

00:30:04.630 --> 00:30:06.752
pretty good trends to follow.

00:30:06.752 --> 00:30:08.710
And we're actually going
to be coming up with--

00:30:08.710 --> 00:30:10.570
probably on Thursday--

00:30:10.570 --> 00:30:14.050
a semi-empirical formula to
get the rough binding energy

00:30:14.050 --> 00:30:17.110
of any particular assembly
of protons and neutrons.

00:30:17.110 --> 00:30:21.580
And it follows experimental
calculations pretty well--

00:30:21.580 --> 00:30:24.382
surprisingly so.

00:30:24.382 --> 00:30:26.090
I want to jump back
to here, because I've

00:30:26.090 --> 00:30:29.720
mentioned cross sections,
and I want to actually define

00:30:29.720 --> 00:30:32.120
what a cross section is,
because this is a quantity

00:30:32.120 --> 00:30:34.850
that you're going to
be using everywhere.

00:30:34.850 --> 00:30:37.130
Let's say that we fired
a beam of particles--

00:30:37.130 --> 00:30:38.960
it doesn't matter what it is--

00:30:38.960 --> 00:30:41.630
at a target of other particles.

00:30:41.630 --> 00:30:44.450
Let's say, the beam
particles are atom A,

00:30:44.450 --> 00:30:46.970
and the target
particles are atom B.

00:30:46.970 --> 00:30:50.210
And once these A particles
pass through the target

00:30:50.210 --> 00:30:52.790
B, a little bit
fewer of them come

00:30:52.790 --> 00:30:56.780
out the other side reacted,
or unscathed, or unscattered.

00:30:56.780 --> 00:31:00.050
And some of them are absorbed,
or scattered, or bounced off,

00:31:00.050 --> 00:31:02.870
or scattered backwards,
or what have you.

00:31:02.870 --> 00:31:04.790
We can write the sort
of proportionality

00:31:04.790 --> 00:31:09.140
constant between the change
in intensity of our A beam

00:31:09.140 --> 00:31:12.230
and the thickness of our slab.

00:31:12.230 --> 00:31:14.000
And we give that
proportionality constant

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:17.500
this symbol, little sigma.

00:31:17.500 --> 00:31:19.490
We'll get something
going up here.

00:31:19.490 --> 00:31:22.225
Little sigma, which we call
the microscopic cross section.

00:31:30.340 --> 00:31:32.970
It's in effect, a constant
of proportionality

00:31:32.970 --> 00:31:35.910
that relates the
probability of absorbing

00:31:35.910 --> 00:31:37.640
an atom from this beam I--

00:31:37.640 --> 00:31:41.220
or from this beam of atoms
A through a slab of B.

00:31:41.220 --> 00:31:43.800
And then if you
take this formula,

00:31:43.800 --> 00:31:46.350
you divide by that delta X--

00:31:46.350 --> 00:31:49.210
so I'm going to
take what's on there

00:31:49.210 --> 00:31:55.530
and say delta I over delta
X equals minus cross section

00:31:55.530 --> 00:31:57.990
ABn--

00:31:57.990 --> 00:32:01.180
which refers here to
the number density.

00:32:01.180 --> 00:32:03.150
So I'll keep our
table of symbols

00:32:03.150 --> 00:32:05.265
altogether so it's a
little easier to follow.

00:32:05.265 --> 00:32:15.490
n is our number density, which
means the number of atoms

00:32:15.490 --> 00:32:17.740
per unit volume.

00:32:17.740 --> 00:32:21.670
Usually, in nuclear
quantities, we use centimeters

00:32:21.670 --> 00:32:24.520
because these are things that
are actually fairly measurable,

00:32:24.520 --> 00:32:26.410
and cross sections
are actually in units

00:32:26.410 --> 00:32:31.880
of centimeters squared.

00:32:31.880 --> 00:32:34.160
And let me finish
that expression.

00:32:34.160 --> 00:32:36.050
We had the number
density of our target

00:32:36.050 --> 00:32:43.300
B. We had our initial
intensity, and that's it.

00:32:43.300 --> 00:32:47.360
Anyone know how to solve
this differential equation?

00:32:47.360 --> 00:32:51.856
If we take the limit
of small deltas,

00:32:51.856 --> 00:32:55.888
it should start to look like
a differential equation.

00:32:55.888 --> 00:32:57.680
The final answer is up
there on the screen.

00:32:57.680 --> 00:32:59.810
Does anyone remember the
method to actually solve

00:32:59.810 --> 00:33:00.935
this differential equation?

00:33:03.920 --> 00:33:04.990
This is the easy one--

00:33:04.990 --> 00:33:07.130
separate the variables.

00:33:07.130 --> 00:33:09.970
So in this case, we can
divide each side by I of of X,

00:33:09.970 --> 00:33:13.720
multiply each side by X.
I'm going to bring this up

00:33:13.720 --> 00:33:16.630
so I'm not bending down.

00:33:16.630 --> 00:33:25.300
So we have dI over I equals
minus sigma ab n of B times dX.

00:33:28.150 --> 00:33:33.340
Integrate both sides
and we get log of I

00:33:33.340 --> 00:33:45.160
equals minus sigma ab n of BX,
and some integration constant.

00:33:45.160 --> 00:33:49.780
You can apply an initial
boundary condition to say at X

00:33:49.780 --> 00:33:53.050
equals zero, the
intensity of the being

00:33:53.050 --> 00:33:55.690
x was some intensity I naught.

00:33:55.690 --> 00:33:57.700
Whatever intensity of the
beam that we initially

00:33:57.700 --> 00:34:00.020
fired at the target.

00:34:00.020 --> 00:34:02.200
And by combining
these two, you end up

00:34:02.200 --> 00:34:04.420
with the expression
you get right there,

00:34:04.420 --> 00:34:08.440
which is that the intensity
of the beam coming out

00:34:08.440 --> 00:34:14.230
is the initial intensity times
e to the minus sigma ab nbx.

00:34:17.320 --> 00:34:19.370
And we've kind of
derived the idea

00:34:19.370 --> 00:34:21.670
of exponential attenuation.

00:34:21.670 --> 00:34:26.480
For those who haven't
seen that word before,

00:34:26.480 --> 00:34:30.440
attenuation or the gradual
removal of the beam of incident

00:34:30.440 --> 00:34:32.870
particles by whatever
the target happens to be.

00:34:36.080 --> 00:34:38.870
This quantity right
here, we actually

00:34:38.870 --> 00:34:45.480
have another symbol for it,
which we give big sigma.

00:34:45.480 --> 00:34:50.248
And in this case, big sigma
we call the macroscopic cross

00:34:50.248 --> 00:34:50.847
section.

00:34:58.490 --> 00:34:59.940
I'll draw a box
around these so we

00:34:59.940 --> 00:35:04.020
know these are our symbols that
we're keeping defined here.

00:35:04.020 --> 00:35:06.960
And so you may see that the
microscopic cross section just

00:35:06.960 --> 00:35:10.575
depends on single reactions
between the incoming atoms

00:35:10.575 --> 00:35:14.970
A and the target atoms B.
The macroscopic cross section

00:35:14.970 --> 00:35:17.650
depends on how much B is there.

00:35:17.650 --> 00:35:22.170
So if you want to get per atom
probabilities of absorption

00:35:22.170 --> 00:35:24.660
scattering, whatever
thing you're looking at,

00:35:24.660 --> 00:35:27.210
you use the microscopic
cross section.

00:35:27.210 --> 00:35:29.980
And if you have a finite
amount of stuff there,

00:35:29.980 --> 00:35:32.640
and you know the number
density of your substance B,

00:35:32.640 --> 00:35:35.790
you can use the
macroscopic cross section

00:35:35.790 --> 00:35:38.910
to get actual total
probabilities of beam

00:35:38.910 --> 00:35:40.260
attenuation--

00:35:40.260 --> 00:35:43.320
or to calculate
exponential attenuation.

00:35:43.320 --> 00:35:45.750
We're going to see this
again in another form when

00:35:45.750 --> 00:35:47.970
we talk about
designing shielding,

00:35:47.970 --> 00:35:49.470
and how much
shielding do you need

00:35:49.470 --> 00:35:51.930
to remove how much of the beam?

00:35:51.930 --> 00:35:54.060
Well, this quantity
right here, there's

00:35:54.060 --> 00:35:57.360
actually tabulated values for
a lot of this stuff at the--

00:35:57.360 --> 00:35:58.680
on the NIST website.

00:35:58.680 --> 00:36:01.500
And I have links to that as
well on the Stellar website,

00:36:01.500 --> 00:36:04.650
so you can-- instead of having
to look these all up on JANIS

00:36:04.650 --> 00:36:06.150
and multiply number
densities, there

00:36:06.150 --> 00:36:08.430
are some easier graphical
functions you can just

00:36:08.430 --> 00:36:10.110
find the value for.

00:36:10.110 --> 00:36:11.880
But we'll get back to
that in a few days.

00:36:14.520 --> 00:36:16.770
So anyway, on reading
the KAERI table,

00:36:16.770 --> 00:36:19.770
there's a few
quantities right there.

00:36:19.770 --> 00:36:22.380
We've already defined
what the excess mass

00:36:22.380 --> 00:36:24.330
and the binding energy is.

00:36:24.330 --> 00:36:25.890
And I want to note
right here, if you

00:36:25.890 --> 00:36:28.710
want to actually calculate
binding energies by hand, which

00:36:28.710 --> 00:36:31.765
I'm going to ask you to
do a bit on problem set 2,

00:36:31.765 --> 00:36:33.765
you'll need to know what
the mass of the proton,

00:36:33.765 --> 00:36:35.910
and the neutron,
and the electron

00:36:35.910 --> 00:36:38.760
are to, again, usually
like six or seven digits

00:36:38.760 --> 00:36:41.970
is the idea behind this course.

00:36:41.970 --> 00:36:45.240
Notice that they're not
exactly one atomic mass unit,

00:36:45.240 --> 00:36:46.860
because one atomic
mass unit, again,

00:36:46.860 --> 00:36:48.523
was set with that
carbon-12 standard.

00:36:48.523 --> 00:36:50.940
I'm not going to use the word
gold standard because that's

00:36:50.940 --> 00:36:54.570
a misnomer in this field.

00:36:54.570 --> 00:36:56.940
And so like I said, what
does excess mass really mean,

00:36:56.940 --> 00:36:58.530
physically?

00:36:58.530 --> 00:37:00.990
Not much, because
it's the comparison

00:37:00.990 --> 00:37:03.900
to an arbitrary standard or
a rather poor approximation

00:37:03.900 --> 00:37:04.890
of the mass.

00:37:04.890 --> 00:37:08.250
The binding energy actually
does represent the conversion

00:37:08.250 --> 00:37:10.290
of mass to energy
when you assemble

00:37:10.290 --> 00:37:15.980
a nucleus like Voltron-style
from its constituent nucleons.

00:37:15.980 --> 00:37:18.070
So let's try a few examples
in class right here.

00:37:18.070 --> 00:37:21.210
I'd like you guys to follow
around and try and calculate

00:37:21.210 --> 00:37:26.700
the binding energy of each of
these three nuclei of sulfur.

00:37:26.700 --> 00:37:31.400
Let me get a better blank
board so we can follow along.

00:37:31.400 --> 00:37:33.660
And there's a few different
ways of calculating

00:37:33.660 --> 00:37:34.980
that binding energy.

00:37:34.980 --> 00:37:37.410
You can do it by
the excess mass.

00:37:37.410 --> 00:37:38.850
You can do it by--

00:37:38.850 --> 00:37:40.630
let's go back to the
table of nuclides

00:37:40.630 --> 00:37:43.240
so I can show you
how I would do it.

00:37:43.240 --> 00:37:45.870
Let's start with sulfur 32.

00:37:45.870 --> 00:37:48.426
And we'll write up the
quantities that we're--

00:37:48.426 --> 00:37:50.000
that we know.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:52.860
Let's say the excess
mass is the actual mass

00:37:52.860 --> 00:37:55.800
minus the mass number.

00:37:55.800 --> 00:38:04.950
The binding energy is Z times
mass of hydrogen plus A minus Z

00:38:04.950 --> 00:38:09.870
mass of a neutron minus the
actual mass of that nucleus

00:38:09.870 --> 00:38:14.100
with AZ c squared.

00:38:14.100 --> 00:38:19.290
And then what we can do is
rearrange this excess mass,

00:38:19.290 --> 00:38:23.120
isolating the mass term right
here, and make a substitution.

00:38:23.120 --> 00:38:26.740
So we can say the
mass is actually

00:38:26.740 --> 00:38:32.820
the excess mass plus A.
Stick that in right there,

00:38:32.820 --> 00:38:35.730
and now we can calculate and
confirm the binding energies

00:38:35.730 --> 00:38:40.170
that we see right here from
tabulated excess mass values,

00:38:40.170 --> 00:38:45.120
atomic number, mass number,
and the masses of a hydrogen

00:38:45.120 --> 00:38:51.330
atom and a neutron,
which, for reference,

00:38:51.330 --> 00:38:54.100
I'll write up here as well.

00:38:54.100 --> 00:38:57.330
So the mass of a
hydrogen is the mass

00:38:57.330 --> 00:39:00.120
of a proton plus an electron.

00:39:00.120 --> 00:39:10.110
So 1.0072-- 007276 plus 0.000--

00:39:10.110 --> 00:39:12.480
make that a little
easier to read--

00:39:12.480 --> 00:39:20.360
how many zeros-- 00054858 AMU.

00:39:20.360 --> 00:39:27.180
Mass of a neutron, surprisingly
close to Chadwick's prediction.

00:39:27.180 --> 00:39:33.120
8664 AMU.

00:39:33.120 --> 00:39:37.420
So now I'll head back to
the table of nuclides.

00:39:37.420 --> 00:39:40.110
And let's see if you
guys can follow along.

00:39:40.110 --> 00:39:42.750
What we want to do is try
to confirm this binding

00:39:42.750 --> 00:39:46.020
energy using the atomic
mass, the excess mass,

00:39:46.020 --> 00:39:48.630
or if we don't even
know the atomic mass,

00:39:48.630 --> 00:39:53.070
we can use the excess
mass plus A right there.

00:39:53.070 --> 00:39:58.650
So let's see-- Z, in this
case, for sulfur, is 16 times

00:39:58.650 --> 00:40:01.740
the mass of hydrogen. This
is definitely a calculator

00:40:01.740 --> 00:40:04.325
moment, because like I said,
I don't know about you guys,

00:40:04.325 --> 00:40:06.450
but I can't do eight
significant digits in my head.

00:40:10.160 --> 00:40:21.930
0054858-- 1.007855--
probably enough digits--

00:40:21.930 --> 00:40:24.510
plus 16, because there's--

00:40:24.510 --> 00:40:26.750
mass number here is 32.

00:40:26.750 --> 00:40:28.050
The atomic number is 16.

00:40:28.050 --> 00:40:32.370
That leaves us with 16 neutrons
times the mass of a neutron,

00:40:32.370 --> 00:40:36.120
08664--

00:40:36.120 --> 00:40:47.670
minus the excess mass, which
in this case is 26.015 MeV--

00:40:47.670 --> 00:40:52.770
015 MeV per c squared.

00:40:52.770 --> 00:40:55.560
So thanks for that-- thank
Jared for that question because,

00:40:55.560 --> 00:40:57.517
indeed, the excess
mass, if you want

00:40:57.517 --> 00:40:59.100
to write it in terms
of a mass, should

00:40:59.100 --> 00:41:04.150
be in MeV or keV per
c squared minus A,

00:41:04.150 --> 00:41:09.090
which is 32 times c squared.

00:41:11.780 --> 00:41:13.490
So let's do all this out--

00:41:13.490 --> 00:41:16.630
shouldn't take too long.

00:41:16.630 --> 00:41:20.730
007825 plus 16--

00:41:20.730 --> 00:41:38.610
1.008664 minus 32 minus
26.015 divided by c squared.

00:41:38.610 --> 00:41:39.740
It's basically nothing.

00:41:42.770 --> 00:41:46.310
Gives us on the order of--

00:41:46.310 --> 00:41:48.845
let's see-- times c squared.

00:42:10.975 --> 00:42:12.100
What did we get right here?

00:42:18.792 --> 00:42:21.182
AUDIENCE: Is the 26 negative?

00:42:21.182 --> 00:42:23.600
MICHAEL SHORT: Ah, let's see.

