00:46:27.520 --> 00:46:33.110
here, the actual boron neutron
capture therapy reaction.

00:46:33.110 --> 00:46:37.360
And now we can get towards
calculating this Q, what

00:46:37.360 --> 00:46:39.910
the difference is between the--

00:46:39.910 --> 00:46:42.460
the total energies of the
products and the reactants,

00:46:42.460 --> 00:46:44.150
and where does that go?

00:46:44.150 --> 00:46:46.540
So now we can either
look up or calculate

00:46:46.540 --> 00:46:49.840
the binding energy of
each of these nuclei,

00:46:49.840 --> 00:46:52.720
subtract off the energy of the
gamma, which I've looked up

00:46:52.720 --> 00:46:59.380
already, is about 0.478 MeV.

00:46:59.380 --> 00:47:02.770
And we can figure out what the
total Q of this reaction is.

00:47:02.770 --> 00:47:03.753
So in this case--

00:47:03.753 --> 00:47:05.170
I'll skip ahead
to the slide where

00:47:05.170 --> 00:47:08.980
I've got it because that way
I won't write anything wrong

00:47:08.980 --> 00:47:10.420
on the board--

00:47:10.420 --> 00:47:12.220
got everything right up here.

00:47:12.220 --> 00:47:14.680
We assume that both
boron and the neutron

00:47:14.680 --> 00:47:16.720
have roughly zero
kinetic energy.

00:47:16.720 --> 00:47:18.700
And at the end,
they come out with

00:47:18.700 --> 00:47:22.180
some other kinetic energies
as well as this gamma ray.

00:47:22.180 --> 00:47:25.960
The sum of this energy
differences, we refer to as Q.

00:47:25.960 --> 00:47:28.930
And we can actually
confirm this total Q

00:47:28.930 --> 00:47:31.195
with a few different methods.

00:47:31.195 --> 00:47:33.070
In this case, it's always
conserve something.

00:47:33.070 --> 00:47:34.750
That's the whole
theme of this course,

00:47:34.750 --> 00:47:36.880
is you can conserve
total masses,

00:47:36.880 --> 00:47:38.650
you can conserve total
kinetic energies.

00:47:38.650 --> 00:47:43.120
We may not know those, but
tabulated in the KAERI table

00:47:43.120 --> 00:47:45.770
are the binding energies
of each of these nuclei.

00:47:45.770 --> 00:47:47.320
So let's try that out right now.

00:47:50.515 --> 00:47:52.390
So let's look at the
binding energies of each

00:47:52.390 --> 00:47:55.090
of these nuclei and see
what the difference is,

00:47:55.090 --> 00:47:56.890
the total energy released.

00:47:56.890 --> 00:48:00.760
First of all, what's the binding
energy of a lone neutron?

00:48:00.760 --> 00:48:02.160
Anyone have any idea?

00:48:02.160 --> 00:48:03.220
I see a lot of these--

00:48:03.220 --> 00:48:03.720
zero.

00:48:03.720 --> 00:48:04.498
Yep.

00:48:04.498 --> 00:48:06.790
You haven't assembled an
nucleus out of a lone neutron,

00:48:06.790 --> 00:48:14.500
so we'll go with the neutron has
a binding energy of zero MeV.

00:48:14.500 --> 00:48:16.480
Boron, not quite
the case, but we

00:48:16.480 --> 00:48:21.160
can go back to the table of
nuclides and punch that in--

00:48:21.160 --> 00:48:24.360
boron-10.

00:48:24.360 --> 00:48:25.800
We can look up its
binding energy,

00:48:25.800 --> 00:48:29.250
which is about 64.7507--

00:48:29.250 --> 00:48:40.200
I keep saying about, which
is exactly 64.7507 MeV.

00:48:40.200 --> 00:48:43.410
And then our other
two nuclei, helium-4--

00:48:43.410 --> 00:48:48.300
so you can punch
in helium-4 here.

00:48:48.300 --> 00:49:03.040
It's got a binding energy
of exactly 28.295673 MeV.

00:49:03.040 --> 00:49:10.055
And finally, lithium-7,
let's punch that in.

00:49:10.055 --> 00:49:11.430
I think you guys
are going to get

00:49:11.430 --> 00:49:12.810
very familiar with this table.

00:49:12.810 --> 00:49:14.580
There's a few
versions out there.

00:49:14.580 --> 00:49:16.380
There's a new slick
Java version that I

00:49:16.380 --> 00:49:17.620
found a little hard to use.

00:49:17.620 --> 00:49:20.520
So I like the text-only version,
