00:49:20.520 --> 00:49:22.410
and fast as it gets--

00:49:22.410 --> 00:49:34.180
39.244526-- 526.

00:49:34.180 --> 00:49:38.770
So any sort of increase in
total amount of binding energy

00:49:38.770 --> 00:49:42.310
between the reactants
and the products

00:49:42.310 --> 00:49:45.190
is going to release
or absorb energy.

00:49:45.190 --> 00:49:49.900
Now because boron does capture
a thermal neutron, or a neutron

00:49:49.900 --> 00:49:53.170
with approximately zero
eV of kinetic energy,

00:49:53.170 --> 00:49:55.210
does anyone have any
idea whether this would

00:49:55.210 --> 00:49:58.450
release or consume energy?

00:49:58.450 --> 00:50:01.450
In other words, do think this
is an exothermic or endothermic

00:50:01.450 --> 00:50:04.120
reaction?

00:50:04.120 --> 00:50:04.817
Yeah, Alex?

00:50:04.817 --> 00:50:06.400
AUDIENCE: I'm guessing
that heat would

00:50:06.400 --> 00:50:08.590
be released through the
material-- the capture

00:50:08.590 --> 00:50:10.350
material would be heated up.

00:50:10.350 --> 00:50:11.140
MICHAEL SHORT: OK.

00:50:11.140 --> 00:50:12.610
Indeed.

00:50:12.610 --> 00:50:14.800
If the total Q value
is greater than zero,

00:50:14.800 --> 00:50:16.390
we refer to this as exothermic--

00:50:18.970 --> 00:50:20.960
kind of like in chemistry.

00:50:20.960 --> 00:50:24.550
And if Q is less than zero, we
refer to this as endothermic.

00:50:27.130 --> 00:50:30.298
So let's do our binding
energy subtraction now.

00:50:30.298 --> 00:50:32.590
We want to figure out how
much excess binding energy is

00:50:32.590 --> 00:50:33.110
released.

00:50:33.110 --> 00:50:35.100
So I'm going to
take the reactants--

00:50:35.100 --> 00:50:36.850
I'm sorry-- I'm going
to take the product.

00:50:36.850 --> 00:50:47.110
So helium 295673--
add lithium 244526--

00:50:47.110 --> 00:50:53.560
subtract boron 0.7507-- subtract
the neutron, which is zero,

00:50:53.560 --> 00:51:01.820
and we're left with 2.79 MeV.

00:51:01.820 --> 00:51:05.265
And because it's positive,
this is an exothermic reaction,

00:51:05.265 --> 00:51:07.640
which is what we'd expect,
because this reaction actually

00:51:07.640 --> 00:51:09.050
happens.

00:51:09.050 --> 00:51:10.970
If this was an
endothermic reaction,

00:51:10.970 --> 00:51:12.660
what could you do
to make it occur?

00:51:17.780 --> 00:51:18.280
Yeah?

00:51:18.280 --> 00:51:21.248
AUDIENCE: Heat up the reactants.

00:51:21.248 --> 00:51:22.790
MICHAEL SHORT: Like
with temperature,

00:51:22.790 --> 00:51:24.384
or what do you mean?

00:51:24.384 --> 00:51:26.753
AUDIENCE: Make them have
higher kinetic energy or--

00:51:26.753 --> 00:51:27.920
MICHAEL SHORT: There you go.

00:51:27.920 --> 00:51:30.378
So actually-- yeah-- you kind
of said the same thing twice.

00:51:30.378 --> 00:51:32.690
Heating things up does give
them higher kinetic energy.

00:51:32.690 --> 00:51:34.107
If you rely on
temperature, you'll

00:51:34.107 --> 00:51:37.425
be imparting eV worth
of kinetic energy.

00:51:37.425 --> 00:51:39.050
But if you accelerate
them, or get them

00:51:39.050 --> 00:51:40.467
from a different
nuclear reaction,

00:51:40.467 --> 00:51:42.810
and you get them up
to the MeV level,

00:51:42.810 --> 00:51:45.590
where whatever this Q value
could be might be negative,

00:51:45.590 --> 00:51:47.760
then you can get the
reaction to occur.

00:51:47.760 --> 00:51:53.390
For example, what is
the Q of that reaction?

00:51:56.708 --> 00:51:59.080
AUDIENCE: Negative 2.79.

00:51:59.080 --> 00:52:00.560
MICHAEL SHORT: Negative that.

00:52:00.560 --> 00:52:03.190
So in this case,
if you want lithium

00:52:03.190 --> 00:52:07.060
to absorb an alpha particle,
and make boron and a neutron,

00:52:07.060 --> 00:52:09.190
you would have to
accelerate the alphas

00:52:09.190 --> 00:52:12.850
to that same amount of energy
in order to get this to occur.

00:52:12.850 --> 00:52:16.600
So nuclear reactions do go
both ways, just not as easily.

00:52:16.600 --> 00:52:18.100
Kind of like chemical
reactions, you

00:52:18.100 --> 00:52:20.290
can drive them in
different directions

00:52:20.290 --> 00:52:22.690
by changing the temperature
or changing the concentration

00:52:22.690 --> 00:52:23.800
of the reactants.

00:52:23.800 --> 00:52:25.730
Here the concentration
doesn't matter.

00:52:25.730 --> 00:52:29.440
But the kinetic energy related
directly to the temperature

00:52:29.440 --> 00:52:31.710
definitely is.

00:52:31.710 --> 00:52:34.740
And so in this
case, it's 2.79 MeV.

00:52:34.740 --> 00:52:39.540
If I tell you the gamma ray
takes off 0.478 MeV of that,

00:52:39.540 --> 00:52:45.150
we're left with 2.31
MeV between the lithium

00:52:45.150 --> 00:52:48.120
nucleus and the helium nucleus.

